values.comments:
This course discusses the foundations of contemporary social science. It focuses on the nature of social systems, the similarities and differences between social and natural sciences, the construction, analysis, and confirmation of social theories, and the nature of social explanations. The course will examine questions about objectivity in the social sciences, and students will construct and analyze simple computational models of social phenomena.&#8232;
&#8232;Students thought that the course “raises some interesting questions,” but overall found subject matter and material “dry,” “boring,” and “dull.” The course was described as “too vague” and “without a serious focus.” There are several required readings, a few “interesting” guest lecturers, and assignments including essays and take-home exams due at the end of the semester. Students unanimously cited “the application of evolutionary biology in the social sciences via agent-based modeling” as the most valuable and enjoyable part of the course.&#8232;&#8232;
Students described Professor Weisberg as an “eloquent speaker” and “very enthusiastic.” He is a “dynamic lecturer and really encouraged class discussions during lecture.” Through his lecture slides, which had “a good combination of information and relevant video clips,” he did a “great job expressing the ideas of a very complicated and intricate subject.” Students were impressed by his methods, one student even describing him as, “by far, the best professor that I have had.”&#8232;&#8232;
This course is required for all PPE majors and is, ultimately, a philosophy class, so “it might be difficult at times to wrap your mind around the concepts.” It is a “challenge” to stay on top of the “very dense” readings.” The complex material indicated to some that this course is only for those interested in the topic, but another student felt it was a “class that any social science student should take,” because it “raised my awareness of what it is I am actually doing in college, and it taught me to approach what I am learning in class with an educated skepticism.” It might be beneficial to take an intro to philosophy writing course first. Most students felt that they would not receive good grades because much of the course is graded based on philosophy essays, which students felt were “graded harshly.”
